         <div type="transcription">
            <p>
<lb corresp="#b_x"/><w>kroś</w><gap reason="editorial"/><w>täṅkässi</w><w>mā</w><w>cämpäṣ</w></p>
         </div>
         <div type="translation">
            <p><choice corresp="#b_x"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">cold ... he cannot stop</seg></seg></choice></p>
         </div>
         <div type="comments">
            <p><note type="lingcomment">On TA <hi>kroś</hi> instead of <hi>k_uraś</hi> (so <bibl><title corresp="ref:krauseandthomas1964"/><citedRange>95</citedRange></bibl>; <bibl><title corresp="ref:carlingetal2009"/><citedRange>152</citedRange></bibl>), see <bibl><title corresp="ref:jietal1998"/><citedRange>286</citedRange></bibl> and <bibl><title corresp="ref:itkin2011"/><citedRange>251-2</citedRange></bibl>.</note><note type="philcomment"><hi>kroś</hi> glosses Skt. <hi>śīta</hi> 'cold'. <hi>täṅkässi mā cämpaṣ</hi> glosses Skt. <hi>pratīghātaṃ notthāpaya(ti)</hi> 'does not arouse resentment'. Apparently <hi>pratīghātaṃ</hi> was taken in the sense 'warding off' and <hi>utthāpayati</hi> in the sense 'can'.</note><note type="remarks">Probably a Vinaya-fragment <bibl><title corresp="ref:idp0000"/></bibl>.</note></p>
         </div>
         <div type="bibliography">
            <p><label>Online access</label><bibl><title corresp="ref:idp0000"/></bibl>; <bibl><title corresp="ref:peyrot2014"/><citedRange>164</citedRange></bibl>; <bibl><title corresp="ref:wille2012"/><citedRange>79</citedRange></bibl>.</p>
         </div>
